Package com.intellij.internal.statistic.service.fus.collectors

Class FUCounterUsageLogger

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.intellij.internal.statistic.service.fus.collectors.FUCounterUsageLogger

  • public class FUCounterUsageLogger
extends java.lang.Object

    Use it to record IDE events e.g. invoked action, opened dialog.


    To implement a new collector:
    1. Record events with logEvent(Project, String, String), logEvent(Project, String, String, FeatureUsageData), logEvent(String, String) or logEvent(String, String, FeatureUsageData);
    2. Register collector in plugin.xml as <statistics.counterUsagesCollector groupId="ID" version="1"/>;
    3. Specify collectors data scheme and implement custom validation rules if necessary.
      For more information see SensitiveDataValidator;
    4. Create an issue to add group, its data scheme and description to the whitelist;
    To test collector:
    1. If group is not whitelisted, add it to local whitelist with "Add Test Group to Local Whitelist" action.
      com.intellij.internal.statistic.actions.localWhitelist.AddTestGroupToLocalWhitelistAction
    2. Open toolwindow with event logs with "Show Statistics Event Log" action.
      com.intellij.internal.statistic.actions.ShowStatisticsEventLogAction
    See Also:
    ApplicationUsagesCollector, ProjectUsagesCollector

      • logEvent

        public void logEvent(Project project,
                     java.lang.String groupId,
                     java.lang.String eventId)
        Records new project-wide event without context.

        For events with context use logEvent(Project, String, String, FeatureUsageData), useful to report structured events.

        Example:
        "eventId": "tooltip.shown"
        Parameters:
        project - shows in which project event was invoked, useful to separate events from two simultaneously opened projects.
        groupId - is used to simplify access to events, e.g. 'dialogs', 'intentions'.
        eventId - should be a verb because it shows which action happened, e.g. 'dialog.shown', 'project.opened'.
        See Also:
        logEvent(Project, String, String, FeatureUsageData)

      • logEvent

        public void logEvent(Project project,
                     java.lang.String groupId,
                     java.lang.String eventId,
                     FeatureUsageData data)
        Records new project-wide event with context.

        Example:
        "eventId": "action.called"
        "data": {"id":"ShowIntentionsAction", "input_event":"Alt+Enter"}
        Parameters:
        project - shows in which project event was invoked, useful to separate events from two simultaneously opened projects.
        groupId - is used to simplify access to events, e.g. 'dialogs', 'intentions'.
        eventId - should be a verb because it shows which action happened, e.g. 'dialog.shown', 'project.opened'.
        data - information about event context or related "items", e.g. "input_event":"Alt+Enter", "place":"MainMenu".

      • logEvent

        public void logEvent(java.lang.String groupId,
                     java.lang.String eventId)
        Records new application-wide event without context.

        For events with context use logEvent(String, String, FeatureUsageData), useful to report structured events.
        For project-wide events use logEvent(Project, String, String), useful to separate events from two simultaneously opened projects.

        Example:
        "eventId": "hector.clicked"
        Parameters:
        groupId - is used to simplify access to events, e.g. 'dialogs', 'intentions'.
        eventId - should be a verb because it shows which action happened, e.g. 'dialog.shown', 'project.opened'.
        See Also:
        logEvent(String, String, FeatureUsageData), logEvent(Project, String, String, FeatureUsageData)

      • logEvent

        public void logEvent(java.lang.String groupId,
                     java.lang.String eventId,
                     FeatureUsageData data)
        Records new application-wide event with context information.

        For project-wide events use logEvent(Project, String, String, FeatureUsageData), useful to separate events from two simultaneously opened projects.

        Example:
        "eventId": "ide.started"
        "data": {"eap":true, "internal":false}
        Parameters:
        groupId - is used to simplify access to events, e.g. 'dialogs', 'intentions'.
        eventId - should be a verb because it shows which action happened, e.g. 'dialog.shown', 'project.opened'.
        data - information about event context or related "items", e.g. "input_event":"Alt+Enter", "place":"MainMenu".
        See Also:
        logEvent(Project, String, String, FeatureUsageData)
